<!-- THESIS -->
<section class="thesis-section" id="intro">
  <div class="thesis-label">Central Argument</div>
  <div class="thesis-body">
    <blockquote>
      "Canada has consistently recruited immigrant labour to power its economy, then failed to integrate those workers as equals — across every era, across every policy reform."
    </blockquote>
    <p>From the 17,000 Chinese men who died building the CPR for one dollar a day, to the Syrian-trained physicians who spend years working as medical assistants because their credentials aren't recognized — the pattern repeats. The tools of exclusion change. The exclusion does not.</p>
    <p>This project traces that history across five chapters: the railway era of explicit exploitation, the prairie settlement era of selective welcome, the 1967 Points System that removed racial barriers on paper, the post-1976 era of growing complexity, and the modern credential recognition crisis that reveals how much unfinished work remains.</p>
    <p>Understanding this history matters because Canada is now one of the most immigration-dependent countries in the developed world. Since 2012, <em>all</em> Canadian labour force growth has come from immigration. Getting immigrant employment right isn't a humanitarian nicety — it's an economic necessity. And we are still getting it wrong.</p>
  </div>
</section>

