<!-- CHAPTER 1: CPR -->
<section class="chapter dark-chapter" id="ch1">
  <div class="chapter-header">
    <div class="chapter-number">01</div>
    <div class="chapter-meta">
      <div class="chapter-era">1881 – 1885 · The Railway Era</div>
      <h2 class="chapter-title">You Must Have This Labour,<br>or You Can't Have the Railway</h2>
      <p class="chapter-subtitle">Prime Minister John A. Macdonald, 1882. The most honest thing the Canadian government ever said about Chinese workers — and the logic that would define immigrant employment for generations.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="chapter-body">
    <div class="chapter-text">
      <p>The Canadian Pacific Railway was the infrastructure that made Canada possible — a ribbon of steel connecting the Pacific coast to the Atlantic, fulfilling the promise that brought British Columbia into Confederation in 1871. Building it required blasting through the Rocky Mountains, a task so dangerous and so labour-intensive that contractors initially couldn't find enough workers willing to do it.</p>
      <p>The solution was 17,000 men from the Guangdong and Fujian provinces of southern China. They came for the same reason immigrants have always come to Canada: the promise of work, and the possibility of a better life. Many planned to send money home to families they had left behind; many hoped to return. Instead, they built a country that didn't want them to stay.</p>
      <p>Chinese workers were paid approximately $1 per day — less than half the wages earned by their white co-workers for identical or more dangerous work. They received no food, no shelter, and no medical care from the CPR. They were assigned the most lethal tasks: drilling through unstable rock, placing explosive charges by hand, hanging from rope baskets over cliff faces. An estimated 600 to 700 died in construction — a figure that historians now consider a significant undercount, since Chinese deaths were often not recorded at all.</p>
      <p>One of the few surviving accounts from a Chinese worker's perspective comes from Dukesang Wong, who kept a diary during construction. After four years of labour, he wrote: "Times for us now are definitely changing, and the fortunes of our people need great care and guarding." His hope was not rewarded. On November 7, 1885 — the date the last spike was driven — the CPR president William Van Horne declared the work "well done in every way." He did not mention the Chinese workers who made it possible.</p>
      <p>Within months, the same federal government that had called Chinese labour indispensable passed the Chinese Immigration Act of 1885, imposing a $50 head tax on any Chinese person entering Canada. The message was unambiguous: you were useful while we needed you. Now you are a problem to be managed. The head tax was raised to $100 in 1900 and $500 in 1903 — equivalent to over $18,000 today, and nearly two years' wages for a railway worker. In 1923, the Chinese Immigration Act effectively banned all Chinese immigration, with fewer than 50 Chinese immigrants admitted to Canada between 1924 and 1947.</p>
      <p>This was not an accident or an oversight. It was policy — the deliberate use of immigrant labour as a commodity, followed by the deliberate exclusion of those workers from the country they built. It is the foundational pattern of Canadian immigrant employment history.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="chapter-aside">
      <div class="stat-card">
        <span class="stat-number">700+</span>
        <span class="stat-label">Chinese Workers Who Died Building the CPR</span>
        <p class="stat-note">Historians consider this a significant undercount — Chinese deaths were often unrecorded.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-card">
        <span class="stat-number">$1/day</span>
        <span class="stat-label">Daily Wage for Chinese Workers</span>
        <p class="stat-note">White workers doing the same work earned $1.50–$2.50/day. Chinese workers also paid for their own food and supplies from this wage.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-card">
        <span class="stat-number">$500</span>
        <span class="stat-label">Head Tax by 1903</span>
        <p class="stat-note">Equivalent to roughly $18,000+ today. Chinese Canadians who served in WWII fought for citizenship, finally granted in 1947. Canada's formal apology came in 2006.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"It is simply a question of alternatives: either you must have this labour or you can't have the railway."</p>
        <cite>— Prime Minister John A. Macdonald, House of Commons, 1882</cite>
      </div>
      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"The CPR treated Chinese workers as if they were commodities, expendable and easily replaceable resources."</p>
        <cite>— NICHE Canada, environmental history journal, 2023</cite>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CHAPTER 2: PRAIRIES -->
<section class="chapter" id="ch2">
  <div class="chapter-header">
    <div class="chapter-number">02</div>
    <div class="chapter-meta">
      <div class="chapter-era">1896 – 1914 · The Prairie Settlement Era</div>
      <h2 class="chapter-title">Only Farmers Need Apply:<br>The Last Best West</h2>
      <p class="chapter-subtitle">Under Minister Clifford Sifton, Canada launched the most aggressive immigration recruitment campaign in its history — and one of the most explicitly racialized.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="chapter-body reverse">
    <div class="chapter-text">
      <p>By the 1890s, Canada faced a crisis: the prairies were empty, and Canadians were leaving — nearly one million had emigrated to the United States during the 1880s, attracted by the American Homestead Act. The newly completed railway had opened the West, but no one was settling it. In 1896, Prime Minister Wilfrid Laurier appointed Clifford Sifton as Minister of the Interior with a single mandate: fill the prairies.</p>
      <p>Sifton's campaign — marketed under the slogan "The Last Best West" — was, in purely logistical terms, one of the most successful immigration drives in world history. Between 1896 and 1914, more than two million settlers poured into the Canadian prairies. In 1913 alone, 400,870 immigrants arrived — a single-year record that has never been broken. The provinces of Alberta and Saskatchewan were created in 1905 largely because enough settlers had arrived to warrant provincial status.</p>
      <p>Sifton's genius was recruitment strategy: he distributed millions of promotional pamphlets across Britain, northern Europe, and the United States, promising 160 free acres of fertile land to anyone who would farm it. He offered commissions to shipping company agents for each qualified immigrant they brought to Canada. He organized tours of the prairies for journalists. He understood, before the age of mass media, how to sell a country.</p>
      <p>But the campaign was explicitly selective in ways that reveal its racial logic. Sifton's preferences, in his own words, were for northern Europeans over southern Europeans, and whites over non-whites. He believed the ideal immigrant was what he called "a stalwart peasant in a sheepskin coat" — someone with experience farming prairie-like conditions, specifically from central and eastern Europe: Ukrainians, Germans, Scandinavians, Doukhobors from Russia. African Americans who wanted to homestead in Alberta were actively discouraged by government agents, despite having extensive farming experience. Asian immigrants remained subject to the head tax and other restrictions.</p>
      <p>The categories of work were rigidly enforced. Sifton did not want urban workers, merchants, or intellectuals — he wanted agricultural labour. Domestics (women, overwhelmingly from Britain) were the second major recruitment category. The government's 1899 archive documents the import of women aged 17 to 35 as domestic servants, with recruitment agencies in London acting as placement firms. By 1906, 4,467 women per year were entering Canada as domestics.</p>
      <p>The prairie settlement era thus reveals the second major theme of this project: that Canada's welcome has never been unconditional. Immigrants were wanted for specific types of labour, in specific locations, of specific ethnic backgrounds. The moment someone fell outside those categories — by arriving from the wrong country, working in the wrong field, or having the wrong skin colour — the welcome evaporated.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="chapter-aside">
      <div class="stat-card" style="background: var(--ink); color: var(--cream);">
        <span class="stat-number">2M+</span>
        <span class="stat-label">Settlers 1896–1914</span>
        <p class="stat-note">The largest immigration wave in Canadian history, driven by Sifton's aggressive recruitment campaign.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-card" style="background: var(--ink); color: var(--cream);">
        <span class="stat-number">400,870</span>
        <span class="stat-label">Immigrants in 1913</span>
