        <p>"A stalwart peasant in a sheepskin coat, born on the soil, is good quality."</p>
        <cite>— Clifford Sifton, Maclean's Magazine, 1922, describing his ideal immigrant</cite>
      </div>
      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"The government attempted to engineer a society that reflected their values... who can say how the Prairie provinces would be different today had they been more successful?"</p>
        <cite>— Historian cited in Canada's History magazine on Sifton's campaign</cite>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CHAPTER 3: POINTS SYSTEM -->
<section class="chapter" id="ch3">
  <div class="chapter-header">
    <div class="chapter-number">03</div>
    <div class="chapter-meta">
      <div class="chapter-era">1967 · The Points System</div>
      <h2 class="chapter-title">Merit Over Race:<br>The Promise and the Problem</h2>
      <p class="chapter-subtitle">The 1967 Immigration Regulations replaced race-based selection with a points system — Canada's most significant immigration reform, and the beginning of new, more subtle inequities.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="chapter-body">
    <div class="chapter-text">
      <p>By the early 1960s, the racial architecture of Canadian immigration policy was increasingly difficult to justify publicly. The Universal Declaration of Human Rights had been adopted in 1948. The civil rights movement was transforming North America. Canada's own Diefenbaker government had passed the Canadian Bill of Rights in 1960. The idea that immigration policy should openly favour white Europeans was becoming untenable.</p>
      <p>In 1962, regulations began dismantling the most explicitly racist elements of the system. In 1967, the Pearson government formalized the transformation: the Points System was born. Independent applicants would now be assessed on nine measurable criteria — education and training, personal character, occupational demand, occupational skill, age, pre-arranged employment, knowledge of French and English, relatives in Canada, and employment opportunities in their destination — and those who scored 50 or more out of 100 points would be admitted.</p>
      <p>The Points System was a genuine reform. It removed the explicit nationality criteria that had governed Canadian immigration since Confederation. It created transparent, standardized standards that applied regardless of where applicants came from. And it worked: before 1967, over 90% of immigrants to Canada came from Europe. By the period 2006–2011, Asia and the Middle East accounted for 56.9% of new arrivals. The Points System diversified Canada in ways that were profound and irreversible.</p>
      <p>But it also created new problems that were not immediately visible. The system was designed to select for skills — but it said nothing about whether those skills would be recognized once immigrants arrived. Canada was now selecting engineers, doctors, lawyers, and accountants from around the world based on their qualifications. It had no mechanism to ensure that, once in Canada, those qualifications would be accepted by Canadian employers and regulatory bodies.</p>
      <p>This gap between selection and integration became the defining challenge of the post-1967 era. Immigrants were admitted because of their credentials. They arrived to find those credentials didn't transfer. They were told their education was "equivalent" but their "Canadian experience" was insufficient. They were overqualified for low-skill jobs and under-recognized for professional positions. The phenomenon became known as "brain waste" — and it would reach crisis proportions by the 21st century.</p>
      <p>The 1967 reform was essential and necessary. But it was only half of a solution. Canada redesigned who it would let in — without redesigning how it would help them thrive.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="chapter-aside">
      <div class="stat-card">
        <span class="stat-number">9</span>
