<!-- CHAPTER 4: TODAY -->
<section class="chapter dark-chapter" id="ch4">
  <div class="chapter-header">
    <div class="chapter-number">04</div>
    <div class="chapter-meta">
      <div class="chapter-era">2000s – 2025 · The Modern Era</div>
      <h2 class="chapter-title">Brain Waste:<br>The Crisis That Keeps Being Rediscovered</h2>
      <p class="chapter-subtitle">Today, Canada admits more immigrants than ever — and continues to systematically underemploy them. The tools of exclusion have changed; the pattern has not.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="chapter-body">
    <div class="chapter-text">
      <p>In 2025, Canada faces a paradox that would be darkly familiar to a Chinese railway worker in 1885: the country needs you, brings you here for your labour, and then creates barriers that prevent you from contributing what you actually know how to do.</p>
      <p>The modern version of this story is called "brain waste" — the systematic underemployment of highly skilled immigrants in jobs far below their qualifications. According to a 2025 C.D. Howe Institute report, overqualified immigrants earn, on average, 46% less than non-immigrants working in the fields they trained for. The rate of overqualification among recent immigrants is three times higher than among Canadian-born workers. According to a 2024 Statistics Canada study, over 25% of immigrants with foreign degrees work in jobs that require only a high school diploma.</p>
      <p>The barriers are structural. In regulated professions like medicine, engineering, nursing, and law, foreign credentials must be assessed by provincial licensing bodies. These processes are complex, expensive, often opaque, and can take years. A physician trained in Syria or India may spend three years working as a medical assistant — if they can find that work — while navigating a requalification maze that costs thousands of dollars and offers no guaranteed outcome. Many give up. Many leave. The phenomenon of "reverse brain drain" — Canada-based immigrants departing for the United States, Australia, or their home countries — has reached its highest levels in two decades.</p>
      <p>The federal government has attempted to address this through programs like the Foreign Credential Recognition Program (2009), Express Entry (2015), and various bridging programs administered provincially. Some progress has been made: British Columbia and Nova Scotia have expedited approvals for healthcare professionals. But experts consistently note that the system remains too fragmented — credential recognition falls under provincial jurisdiction, creating thirteen different frameworks across thirteen jurisdictions — and too slow relative to the speed at which the labour market needs skilled workers.</p>
      <p>What makes this history remarkable is its continuity. In 1885, Chinese workers were useful for building the railway and then excluded by law. In 1904, British women were imported as domestic servants because that was the work deemed appropriate for them. In 1967, skilled workers from Asia were admitted for the first time — then found their skills weren't recognized. In 2025, Canada selects the world's most credentialed immigrants through Express Entry, then watches them drive taxis and work cashier shifts while their medical or engineering degrees sit on a shelf. The tools have changed; the pattern has not. The question is whether it ever will.</p>
    </div>
